1 Principal Component Analysis PCA

1.1 Data Points and Centering

  • Create data matrix X of 1000 data points in 2-dimensional space i.e.Â 1000 rows and 2 columns. (Donât worry about how.)
# Create 1000 data points X
set.seed(1)
n <- 1000
mu <- c(8, -5)
C <- matrix(c(3, 1.5, 1.5, 1), 2, 2)
X <- rep(mu, each=n) + matrix(rnorm(n * 2), n, 2) %*% chol(C) # n-by-d
colnames(X) <- c('x1', 'x2')

head(X)
            x1        x2
[1,]  6.914950 -4.975042
[2,]  8.318080 -4.284994
[3,]  6.552649 -6.159064
[4,] 10.763107 -3.513081
[5,]  8.570724 -4.679940
[6,]  6.578907 -6.541871
# Plot data
plot(X[,1], X[,2], col=rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha=0.3), asp=1, xlab='x1', ylab='x2',
     main=paste(n, 'Data Points | Corr =', round(cor(X[,1], X[,2]), 4)))
grid()
points(mu[1], mu[2], col='#FFC90E', cex=3, lwd=5)

  • Create centered data matrix Xc. Each column has mean 0.
# Center the data

1.2 Major and Minor Axes of Data Ellipsoid?

  • Scatter plot of the data point âcloudâ usually looks like an ellipse with a major axis and a minor axis.
  • Variation of the data is highest along the direction of the major axis.
v1 <- c(0.8808331, 0.4734270) # Unit vector of major axis
v2 <- c(-0.4734270, 0.8808331) # Unit vector of minor axis

# Plot axes of data ellipsoid
plot(Xc[,1], Xc[,2], col=rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha=0.3), asp=1, xlab='x1', ylab='x2',
     main=paste(n, 'Centered Data Points | Corr =', round(cor(Xc[,1], Xc[,2]), 4)))
grid()
lines(c(0, v1[1]) * 5, c(0, v1[2]) * 5, col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=3)
lines(c(0, v2[1]) * 1.5, c(0, v2[2]) * 1.5, col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=3)
points(0, 0, col='#FFC90E', cex=3, lwd=5)

1.3 Projection To Lower-Dimensional Space?

  • If we wish to reduce the 2-dimensional data Xc into just 1-dimensional information, then it seems a good idea to project the data onto the major axis in order to retain the largest amount of variation in the data i.e.Â minimial loss of information.
# Orthogonal projection of each row of data in Xc onto v1
Xk <- (Xc %*% v1 / sum(v1 * v1)) %*% t(v1) 

# Plot projected data
plot(Xk[,1], Xk[,2], col=rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha=0.3), asp=1, xlab='x1', ylab='x2',
     main=paste(n, 'Projected Data Points | k = 1'))
grid()
lines(c(0, 0.881 * 5), c(0, 0.473 * 5), col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=3) # Major axis
lines(c(0, -0.473 * 1.5), c(0, 0.881 * 1.5), col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=3) # Minor axis
points(0, 0, col='#FFC90E', cex=3, lwd=5)

1.5 Overview

  • In practice, instead of projecting the data onto the major axis directly, we do the following:
             x1          x2
[1,] -1.0648747  0.04317617
[2,]  0.3382547  0.73322425
[3,] -1.4271760 -1.14084588
[4,]  2.7832826  1.50513804
[5,]  0.5908994  0.33827847
[6,] -1.4009178 -1.52365235

  • Use an appropriate orthogonal matrix \(Q\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\) (from singular value decomposition SVD) to rotate the centered data Xc so it becomes axis-aligned.
  • Mathematically, this transforms the data Xc from its original coordinates to another rotated coordinates system.
  • Statistically, being âaxis-alignedâ means the \(d\) columns of explanatory variables in the rotated data Xr are now uncorrelated. In other words, this rotation âde-correlatesâ the original data.
             v1           v2
[1,] -0.9175361  0.542171415
[2,]  0.6450741  0.485709261
[3,] -1.7972111 -0.329231143
[4,]  3.1641804  0.008094282
[5,]  0.6806339  0.018219152
[6,] -1.9553129 -0.678851131

  • Since the rotated data Xr is now axis-aligned, projection onto the first few dimensions is straight-forward.
  • Simply keep the first (letâs say) \(k\) coordinates that capture the highest variances and truncate / discard the remaining \(d - k\) columns of variables in data Xr
  • This \(k\)-dimensional data is the result of PCA dimension reduction.
             v1 v2
[1,] -0.9175361  0
[2,]  0.6450741  0
[3,] -1.7972111  0
[4,]  3.1641804  0
[5,]  0.6806339  0
[6,] -1.9553129  0

  • (Optional) For visualization, we could un-rotate the lower \(k\)-dimensional data back to the original \(d\)-dimensional coordinates using the inverse transformation \(Q^{-1}\) (which equals \(Q^T\)).
  • However, in practice, we usually just use the reduced \(k\)-dimensional data above as input to a machine learning model.
             x1         x2
[1,] -0.8081961 -0.4343864
[2,]  0.5682026  0.3053955
[3,] -1.5830431 -0.8508483
[4,]  2.7871148  1.4980084
[5,]  0.5995249  0.3222305
[6,] -1.7223043 -0.9256979

1.6 Singular Value Decomposition SVD

# Compute SVD on centered data Xc
output <- svd(Xc)
U <- output$u # n-by-d
D <- output$d # d-tuple
V <- output$v # d-by-d

dim(U) # n-by-d
[1] 1000    2
head(U)
            [,1]          [,2]
[1,] -0.01437202 -0.0371726842
[2,]  0.01010426 -0.0333014891
[3,] -0.02815101  0.0225729402
[4,]  0.04956283 -0.0005549591
[5,]  0.01066126 -0.0012491512
[6,] -0.03062747  0.0465437957
c(sum(U[,1] ** 2), sum(U[,2] ** 2), sum(U[,1] * U[,2])) # Verify columns of U are orthonormal
[1] 1.000000e+00 1.000000e+00 1.986627e-16
D # Singular values sigma_i
[1] 63.84181 14.58521
V
          [,1]       [,2]
[1,] 0.8808331  0.4734270
[2,] 0.4734270 -0.8808331
t(V) %*% V # Verify V is orthogonal matrix
     [,1] [,2]
[1,]    1    0
[2,]    0    1
max(abs(Xc - U %*% diag(D) %*% t(V))) # Verify Xc = U * D * V^T
[1] 1.454392e-14
# Plot axes of data ellipsoid i.e. columns of V
plot(Xc[,1], Xc[,2], col=rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha=0.3), asp=1, xlab='x1', ylab='x2',
     main=paste(n, 'Centered Data Points | Corr =', round(cor(Xc[,1], Xc[,2]), 4)))
grid()
lines(c(0, V[1,1]), c(0, V[2,1]), col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=1)
lines(c(0, V[1,2]), c(0, V[2,2]), col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=1)
points(0, 0, col='#FFC90E', cex=3, lwd=5)

# Rotate the centered data using V
Xr <- Xc %*% V # Same as U * D

# Plot the centered and rotated data
plot(Xr[,1], Xr[,2], col=rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha=0.3), asp=1, xlab='v1', ylab='v2',
     main=paste(n, 'Rotated Data Points | Corr =', round(cor(Xr[,1], Xr[,2]), 4)))
grid()
lines(c(0, 1), c(0, 0), col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=1)
lines(c(0, 0), c(0, 1), col='#2083C5', lwd=5, lty=1)
points(0, 0, col='#FFC90E', cex=3, lwd=5)

# Covariance matrix Cov(X) of data Xc
C
         x1       x2
x1 3.213152 1.612543
x2 1.612543 1.079645

eigen(C)
eigen() decomposition
$values
[1] 4.0798561 0.2129413

$vectors
           [,1]       [,2]
[1,] -0.8808331  0.4734270
[2,] -0.4734270 -0.8808331
Q <- eigen(C)$vectors
lambda <- eigen(C)$values

Q %*% diag(lambda) %*% t(Q) # Verify same as C
         [,1]     [,2]
[1,] 3.213152 1.612543
[2,] 1.612543 1.079645
Q # Principal components using Cov(X)
           [,1]       [,2]
[1,] -0.8808331  0.4734270
[2,] -0.4734270 -0.8808331

          [,1]       [,2]
[1,] 0.8944272 -0.5547002
[2,] 0.4472136  0.8320503
# Percentage of variance explained along each principal component direction
lambda / sum(lambda)
[1] 0.95039568 0.04960432
